INSERT INTO user_chat_messages VALUES(195,'26861e62-c5a2-4fb9-87e6-ef2d719a5643','model',replace('I feel that pain, Grady. The silence after hitting "submit" is often the most stressful part of the process, especially when you’re used to moving at the speed of a startup.\n\nIf you’re talking about an **Emergent Ventures** grant (which is usually the context with Tyler), here is some perspective that might help lower your blood pressure:\n\n### 1. "Fast" is relative\nTyler is famous for being faster than traditional institutions—where grants take 6 to 12 months—but "fast" in his world usually means **2 to 4 weeks**, not necessarily one week. While there are legendary stories of people hearing back in 24 hours, those are the outliers, not the norm.\n\n### 2. The "High-Context" Factor\nGiven that you are the Head Researcher and CEO of Alignment, your application probably wasn''t a simple request for travel money. If you pitched something complex regarding AGI safety or a new research direction, it requires more cognitive load to process. He might be sitting on it to think it through, or perhaps running it by a specific advisor in the AI safety space.\n\n### 3. The Calendar\nLooking at today''s date (December 8), you are hitting the pre-holiday crunch. Academics and public intellectuals are often swamped right now trying to clear their desks before the end of the year.\n\n**My advice?**\nSit tight. One week of silence is absolutely not a rejection in this context. If you haven''t heard anything in another two weeks (around the 3-week mark), a very polite, short nudge is usually acceptable with EV.\n\nWhat exactly did you pitch him? Was it funding for a specific Alignment project or something broader?','\n',char(10)),'null','null','2025-12-08 06:53:15.967787',NULL);
